"Sampling\n\nMAFE combines random sampling of households and individuals in cities in origin countries, with quota sampling among migrant populations in destination countries. Overall, between early 2008 and early 2010, more than 4,000 household questionnaires and 4,000 individual biographies were successfully completed in 3 African countries (Senegal, Ghana, RD Congo), and around more than 1,400 biographies of African migrants were collected in six European countries (Belgium, France, Italy, The Netherlands, Spain, UK).\n\nSelection Criteria\n\nHouseholds: They were randomly selected to be\nrepresentative of the regions surveyed in Africa. Households\nreporting migrants abroad and/or return migrants were\nover-sampled.\n\nIndividuals: The target population is defined\nusing the same criteria in departure and destination countries in\norder to maximize the samples\u2019 homogeneity:\n\nRespondents are aged 25-75 at the time of the\nsurvey;\n\nRespondents were born in the departure country\n(DR Congo, Ghana, Senegal);\n\nRespondents have (or have had) the citizenship of the\ndeparture country;\n\nIn Europe only, migrants were included only if they had\nemigrated out of Africa at 18 or later, for a stay of at\nleast one year.\n\nIndividuals were selected to fill four strata according to their\nmigration status:\n\nMigrants at the time of the survey (surveyed\nin Europe only);"
