"Ark. panel clarifies director hired temporarily\n\nThe board voted Tuesday to hire Sheila Sharp as the interim director of the Department of Community Correction.\n\nComment\n\nBy Associated Press\n\nStuttgart Daily Leader - Stuttgart, AR\n\nBy Associated Press\n\nPosted Jul. 3, 2013 at 8:37 AM\n\nBy Associated Press\nPosted Jul. 3, 2013 at 8:37 AM\n\nLITTLE ROCK, Ark.\n\nThe Arkansas Board of Corrections is clarifying that the woman it picked to lead the state's parole and probation system is only doing so on a temporary basis.\n\nThe board voted Tuesday to hire Sheila Sharp as the interim director of the Department of Community Correction. The board on Monday voted to hire Sharp but omitted the word \"interim\" in its motion.\n\nSharp is a deputy director at the state Department of Correction, where she's worked for 15 years. She replaces David Eberhard, who abruptly announced his retirement Monday.\n\nEberhard's departure comes as his office faces questions about its handling of a case involving a Little Rock man accused in a May killing. That man was allowed to remain on parole despite multiple felony charges since his 2008 prison release."
"'Every Other Wave'\n\nFirst Place winner in CL's Fiction Contest 2019\n\nBy LINDSEY BAKERWednesday February 6, 2019 01:10 pm EST\n\nHolding a 12-pack of beer and waiting for Mark to finish pumping gas, I noticed that every other car driving down Grove had a headlight out. Mark told me it happened like this \u2014 first you notice two of something, then everything is the same. Soon all you have is pattern. After the fourth pair of cars went by with one car normal, one car winking, I felt lightheaded.\n\nMark pulled up. He was much older than me, but he didn\u2019t do the things that older men do. Things like build ships sideways in bottles with long-nosed tweezers, wear loafers without socks, put their wallets in the same place every day so their pants have one ghost-lined pocket. One winking pocket. Instead he cleaned pools, went surfing, aged harder in the sun. I met him on the ocean.\n\nI put the beer in the trunk and sat down. We were fighting before and I wanted him to apologize, but I didn\u2019t feel the same indignation anymore. Like most things, it faded with distraction. We were headed to a beach gathering"
