"Starbucks also invested $25 million in Square and its CEO Howard Schultz will join Square\u2019s board.\n\nThe deal gives Starbucks a discount on Square\u2019s normal processing fee of 2.75 percent. Starbucks will pay 2.05 percent, according to private company research firm PrivCo. It\u2019s unlikely Starbucks will save a significant amount of money, said Sam Hamadeh, PrivCo\u2019s CEO. He pointed to the fact that Starbucks stock had fallen 19 cents by the afternoon.\n\nHowever, Hamadeh said handling Starbucks\u2019 millions of transactions at 6,800 company-owned stores will bring Square an additional $120 million in revenues and $10 million in profit in 2013. But more than anything, he said it\u2019s about the ripple effect for Square.\n\n\u201cThis is the first time mobile payments has been taken mainstream,\u201d Hamadeh said. \u201cI guarantee smaller merchants will take notice of what 6,800 Starbucks stores are doing, and there are definitely meetings taking place on Sand Hill Road about what mobile payment companies are doing,\u201d he said, referring to Menlo Park\u2019s famed VC corridor.\n\nAfter some angel investments are finalized, Hamadeh said Square\u2019s series D financing could come in at $240 million, which would then value Square at $3.24 billion."
"Undersupply issue worsens\n\nBy\nwebmaster\n\nPosted on Tuesday, 25 January 2011\n\n0\n\nshares\n\nThe Housing Industry Association (HIA) is urging the government to address the barriers constraining housing supply.\n\nAccording to a new report by the Association, Australia\u2019s house prices as a ratio of household income have been rapidly growing for some time now in both capital city and regional areas, making it increasingly difficult for first home buyers to transition from the rental market into home ownership.\n\n\u201cMany first home buyers are not in a position to make the transition to home ownership as they simply cannot afford it. HIA research shows that while many factors contribute to the housing affordability picture, a major cause of falling affordability is that house price growth has outpaced growth in average wages over recent years,\u201d HIA chief executive - association Graham Wolfe said.\n\nMr Wolfe said poor affordability levels in both capital and regional housing markets have stemmed from large structural supply side obstacles that could be alleviated by careful and considered reformation by government.\n\n\u201cIt?s time that serious and urgent policy action is taken to ensure there is sufficient serviced land for residential building in Australia. Expensive land prices are due"
