"Gasherbrum 1\n8068m\n\nAskole, 3105m, Baltistan\n\nToday we arrived in the remote village of Askole by jeep from Skardu, during a 6 hours, 150 km, wild ride. We are at about 950 km distance from Islamabad and this is the point where tomorrow at 6,30 in the morning we will start our 7 days trek to the Base Camp. The porters are ready, some of them being hired along the way, some being local villagers. Askole lies in one of the most fairy tale destinations I have ever seen. Few houses side by side on a grassy terrace. Mountains everywhere. And the poorness. Of course, we cannot speak about electricity here. The people and their cattle live almost side by side. No glass windows, no floors. The local teacher told me they think they ancestors came from Tibet long time ago. Couldn\u2019t say more. A time suspended village to remind me of the basic things that we in Romania are taking for granted but almost never notice or appreciate it for what it worth\u2019s. The video images speak for themselves."
"Thursday, August 14, 2014\n\nThe St. Louis Cardinals stayed in the thick of the National League Central race with a 5-2 win over the Miami Marlins on Wednesday night. Matt Carpenter went 3-for-5 with two runs scored, while Justin Masterson dominated, allowing no runs on three hits in seven innings or work. There was a bit of concern when left fielder Matt Holliday left the game with knee discomfort. He went 0-for-3 and was replaced by Peter Bourjos.\n\nDerrick Goold, who covers the Cardinals for the St. Louis Post-Dispatch, tweeted the following on Holliday's status.\n\nMatt Holliday was removed from the game when his left knee \"flared up.\" He said he expects to play tomorrow. #stlcards#cardinals\n\u2014 Derrick Goold (@dgoold) August 14, 2014\n\nHolliday, in his 11th Major League season, is batting .267 with 12 home runs and 59 RBI this season. The veteran has played for the Rockies, A's and Cardinals. Holliday has had two seasons with 30 or more home runs, five seasons with 100 or more RBI and eight seasons with a batting average of .300 or better. Holliday is a career .308 hitter with 263 home runs and 1,025 RBI."
