"Men's Volleyball\n\nRogers and Dalhausser Win Opening AVP Event\n\nApr 17, 2007\n\nApril 17, 2007\n\nMiami, Fla. -\nFomer UCSB standout Todd Rogers and beach partner Phil Dalhausser picked up where they left off last season and won the opening event of the 2007 AVP Tour Sunday. The team defeated Jake Gibb and Sean Rosenthal in straight sets at the Miami Open.\n\nScores were 21-14 and 21-18.\n\nRogers and Dalhausser have won three consecutive tour events as they concluded their 2006 campaign with victories at the Cincinnati Open and the Lake Tahoe Best of the Beach. Overall, the duo won eight AVP Tour titles last season.\n\nGibb, who had won the previous two AVP openers, had his streak snapped.\n\nDalhausser, the 2006 AVP Best Offensive Player, and Rogers, the reigning Best Defensive Player, defeated the top-seeded squad of Stein Metzger and Mike Lambert in sweeping fashion in the semifinals."
"Mini Mokwa Gourd Seeds (Benincasa hispida var chieh-qua)\n\nThis early variety produces short cylindrical fruits that mature to about 6\u201d long by 3-4\u201d in diameter. They are sweet and mild with succulent flesh. This gourd is has heat and stress tolerant.\n\nIn flavor, this vegetable is similar to courgettes, which is the French name for zucchini. Mokwa Long fruit is best harvested at 5\" to 6\". It is produce cute fruits with and bottle shaped.\n\nLike all hairy melons or jointed gourds, a downy hair covers the skin, which is medium green with white spots. You can remove the hair by peeling or scrubbing, or let it disappear in cooking. Like other jointed gourds, Mokwa Long are best when cut and cooked lightly - steamed or stir-fried - or added to soup. It has a good sweet taste, you mokwa gourd as a substitute for zucchini. To retain best flavor, do not overcook. Cut into chunks for steaming, stir frying, soups or braising. Stuff hollowed melons with meat and bake."
